Xarray Overview#

This is an overview of xarray! I would highly suggest checking out the Project Pythia content too!

import xarray as xr
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from datetime import datetime

Opening a dataset#

ds = xr.open_dataset('mrg10_P3_20181003_R5.nc')

sghowell@hawaii.edu; phone: 808-956-5185; address: Univ. Hawaii Dep't Ocean, 1000 Pope Rd, Honolulu, HI 96822 PLATFORM: NASA P-3B, using a solid diffuser inlet on the port side outside the front cabin. LOCATION: Contained in aircraft data files. ASSOCIATED_DATA: N/A INSTRUMENT_INFO: DATA_INFO: Two TSI 3563 nephelometers were plumbed in series in the front of the plane with a 1 micrometer 50% size cut impactor optionally in line between them, electronically controlled via a 3-way valve. Flow was controlled at 30 liters/minute (volumetric). The TSI Neph scattering coefficients have been corrected for 0 - 180 degrees from the nephelometer detection angles (7 - 170 degrees) based on Anderson and Ogren, Aerosol Science and Technology, 1998. Two Radiance Research M903 nephelometers were operated in parallel at 5 lpm in the rear of the plane. RRDry was operated at ambient relative humidity while RRWet relative humidity was maintained near 80-85 % via a humidity controller upstream. The RR nephelometers' stock filters were replaced with Corion CA-550 80 nm bandpass filters for an effective operating wavelength of 540+/-3 nm (the RR flash lamps have a blue bias). Calibrations were performed in field with refrigerant R-134A (1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane). Measurements are reported at 1 Hz, but mixing time in the nephelometers is about 6 seconds. While negative values are physically absurd, they are a product of noise in the system and are left in so averages are valid. Scattering measurements have been adjusted to standard conditions (1013.25 hPa, 273.15 K), but not for the RH changes that would ensue. UNCERTAINTY: Accuracy for the TSI Nephs is roughly 10%, and depends on averaging times. The RR Nephs lack geometric corrections, so are less accurate, by up to 50% in coarse aerosol (though that was rare in ORACLES). Temperature errors are about 0.5 C and RH errors are roughly 3%. Pressure errors are about 1.5%. ULOD_FLAG: -7777 ULOD_VALUE: N/A LLOD_FLAG: -8888 LLOD_VALUE: N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO: freitag@hawaii.edu; phone: 808-956-7777; University of Hawaii Department of Oceanography, 1000 Pope Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822 PROJECT_INFO: ORACLES 2018 deployment to Sao Tome, September and October, https://espo.nasa.gov/missions/oracles STIPULATIONS_ON_USE: This is the revised dataset with all corrections implemented. However, it is strongly recommended to consult the PI for any updates and interpretation of measurements before publication. OTHER_COMMENTS: N/A REVISION: R1 R1: The following changes have been made: The manual cloud shatter mask was amended using King hot wire probe LWC and Cloud Droplet Probe droplet concentration measurements were necessary. Nephelometer data have been time shifted and are aligned with wing probe PCASP instrument now. TSI I backscattering data for all wavelengths are masked for all flights now since the sensor did not work properly. TSI I 450 nm scattering also tended to drift upward during flight and was recalibrated by repeatedly zeroing the TSI I instrument during flight. TSI II was not operational until October 7th, 2018. R0: This is a preliminary dataset; not all corrections have been implemented. In particular, cloud droplet shatter may still be a problem; a manual mask was applied, but not fully examined. Periods when filters were applied in flight to check for leaks have been removed. A rough correction has been made to account for delays in sample lines synchronizing the TSI 3563 and M903 nephelometers with wing probe PCASP instrument. Post-deployment calibrations are not complete. While RH probes in TSI 3563 and M903 have been corrected based on lab calibrations, RH inside TSI nephelometer is a long-standing problem since the sample is heated by the light and an RH probe cannot be placed in the actual sampling region. Rear PSAP lambda-average Single scattering albedo for 660 nm light 0 74 PI_CONTACT_INFO: sghowell@hawaii.edu; phone: 808-956-5185; University of Hawaii Department of Oceanography, 1000 Pope Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822 PLATFORM: NASA P-3B, using a solid diffuser (SDI; 2016-18) and counterflow virtual impactor (CVI; 2017-18) inlet on the port side outside the front cabin. LOCATION: Contained in aircraft data files. ASSOCIATED_DATA: N/A INSTRUMENT_INFO: DATA_INFO: Two Radiance Research 3-wavelength PSAPS were operated during ORACLES 2016 - 2018 both measuring total aerosol absorption (for aerosol inlet efficiencies see McNaughton (Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 2007)). To reduce artifacts due to changing RH, the PSAP optical block was heated to approximately 50 C during 2016 and 30 C during 2017/18. Absorption data provided here are calculated by the PSAP firmware, which has known calculation issues, decreasing signal to noise. Campaigns 2016/17 used the original PSAP firmware, while both PSAPs were upgraded to version 2.03 for 2018 to improve raw data reporting. The new firmware version for 2018 reduces smoothing times, increasing second by second noise (see UNCERTAINTY info below). The PSAP firmware absorption includes a Bond (2007) correction which was undone before Virkkula (2010) corrections were applied to all PSAP measurements. This submission data set provides both wavelength- specific ("Lambda_Spec_") and wavelength-averaged ("Lambda_Avg_") Virkkula corrections (for details see Table 1 in Virkkula (Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 2010)). The Virkkula (2010) scattering correction and SSA use (interpolated Scat470/Scat530/Scat660) data from the TSI nephelometer (corrected according to Anderson and Ogren; Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 1998). For the 2016 and 2018 campaigns TSI nephelometer total scattering is used exclusively. For the year 2017 both total ("TSI_Impactor_Status" is 1) and submicron ("TSI_Impactor_Status" is 0) TSI nephelometer measurements are used because only one TSI nephelometer was operational (this TSI Neph was operated behind an impactor occasionally during 2017). The effect of submicron TSI measurements on the Virkkula (2010) scattering correction is expected to be small in the free troposphere in the absence of dust but does affect data in the marine boundary layer (MBL) due to sea spray. MBL data during times where submicron TSI measurements were used should be interpreted with care. An alternative to submicrometer TSI data exists via Radiance Research M903 nephelometer data (at 540 nm light). The M903 nephelometer data can be found in the SCAT_P3_YYYYMMDD_RX.ict files. During ORACLES 2016 both PSAPS were operated on the SDI exclusively and in parallel on the second rack from the inlet. After an instrument rearrangement aboard the NASA P-3B, ORACLES campaigns 2017 and 2018 had one PSAP on the front rack next to the SDI/CVI (Front PSAP operated on CVI occasionally), while the other PSAP was on the 4th rack (Rear PSAP operated on the SDI at all times). Variable names designate PSAP unit as either "_Rear" or "_Front" for all 3 years for uniformity of data sets even though instruments were operated on the same rack during 2016. UNCERTAINTY:1 Hz data have considerable random noise. Averaging for 240 - 300 s gives ~ 0.5 Mm^^{-1} errors after Virkkula (2010) corrections (Anderson (JGR; 2009), McNaughton (ACP; 2009), McNaughton (ACP; 2011)). Rapid RH changes also cause periods of increased error. To reduce noise and to achieve closure between both instruments a minimum average of 10 seconds is recommended for both PSAPs. PSAP measurements behind the CVI (Front PSAP; 2017/18 campaign) are also masked and will be submitted in separate files. The PSAP spot size correction has been updated for all 3 years roughly increasing all PSAP ("_Rear" and "_Front") measurements by 5%. R1: The following changes have been made: The manual cloud shatter mask was amended using King hot wire probe LWC and Cloud Droplet Probe droplet concentration measurements were necessary. R0: This is a preliminary dataset and not all corrections have been implemented. In particular, cloud droplet shatter may still be a problem (manual mask was applied, but not fully examined). A rough correction has been made to account for delays in sample lines synchronizing the PSAPs with wing probe PCASP instrument. Post-deployment calibrations are not complete. INSTRUMENT_INFO:Flight-Probe Dual-Range Phase Doppler Interferometer Data From Aritum Model 3321. There are no flags. If there is no data present at a certain time there were no clouds. Comparisons with other cloud probe/instruments does not require any conversion. Measurement Technique described in Chuang P. Y. and Saw and E. W. Small J. D. and Shaw R. A. and Sipperley C. M. and Payne and G. A. and Bachalo W. D. 2008: Airborne phase Doppler interferometry for cloud microphysical measurements Aerosol Sci. Tech. 42 685-703. DATA_INFO:Cloud droplet measurements are reported at observed altitude (temperature and pressure). Cloud drops are measured indivdually and then binned into the the size reanges described above. Units are in micrometers UNCERTAINTY:drop sizing is +/- 0.5 um ULOD_FLAG:-7777 ULOD_VALUE:N/A LLOD_FLAG:-8888 LLOD_VALUE:N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO:Jennifer Griswold (smalljen@hawaii.edu) PROJECT_INFO:ORACLES 2018 STIPULATIONS_ON_USE:These are level R2 and can be used for publication. It is advised that users consult with the PI for information and questions regarding the data product. OTHER_COMMENTS:Data are logarithmically binned. REVISION:R2 R2:View volumes were calculated with new automated algorithm. Data collection was filtered to reduce aircraft noise during flight. R1:Data is time synched with UND CAS and CDP and uses preliminary concentration values. Later revisions will use a comprehenisve method to derive view volume length and thus the concentration. LOCATION: Aircraft location data decribed elsewhere. ASSOCIATED_DATA: see http://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles INSTRUMENT_INFO: The WISPER system centers around two Water Vapor Isotopic Analyzers (Picarro L2120-i and L2120-fi) which utilize cavity-ringdown tunable diode laser spectoscopy. Air for in-situ sampling was collected through two inlets: one was the isokinetic SDI inlet and the other was the Oregon State University counterflow virtual impactor (CVI) inlet. The first analyzer, Pic1, was capable of sampling from either the SDI or CVI inlet, while the second analyzer, Pic2, sampled from only the SDI inlet. For the 2016 deployment, the CVI was not present and therefore only Pic2 variables are available. DATA_INFO: Variables with subscript 'tot2' (i.e. h2o_tot2, dD_tot2, ...) are Pic2 measurements via the SDI inlet, which are total water measurements (vapor+liquid+ice). Since only Pic2 was present for the 2016 deployment, only subscript 2 variables are present. Variables with subscript 'tot1' are Pic1 measurements via the SDI inlet, and are total water measurements as well. Variables with subcript cld (i.e. h2o_cld, dD_cld, ...) are Pic1 measurements of cloud water only (liquid+ice), via the CVI. 'tot1' and 'cld' variables are present for both the 2017 and 2018 deployments. Cloud data where the measured humidity after enchancement is less than 800 ppmv has been masked. However, even at 800 ppmv the isotope ratio measurements are not highly precise or acaurate. If better quality is desired, it is recommended to mask data for humidities below 1500 ppmv. See the 'OTHER_COMMENTS' section below for an overview of instrument performance and data quality for particular flights. Due to incomplete isotope ratio calibration data, the isotope variables in this dataset should not be compared to other datasets on an absolute scale or used for analyses where an absolute scale is necessary. See the section 'UNCERTAINTY' for more info. UNCERTAINTY: Precision: Precision: Estimates of isotope ratio precisions are included as standard deviation columns. The precision for humidity is likely negligible for most studies and columns are not included - if needed, they can assumed to be 35 ppmv for humidities below 6000 ppmv, and 15 ppmv for higher humidities; Accuracy: Due to incomplete absolute calibration data, the isotope variables in this dataset should not be compared to other datasets on an absolute scale or used for analyses where an absolute scale is necessary. However, the dataset is self consistent - i.e. relative changes in values within a flight, between separate flights, and between separate years can be taken as real, within uncertainty. For an estimate of these uncertainties, please contact the PI (see DM_CONTACT_INFO below), or Dean Henze at henzede@oregonstate.edu. Absolute calibration of the humidity measurements can be assumed, with an accuracy of +/-2.5% for values above 6000 ppmv, +/-3.5% for values between 4000 and 6000 ppmv, and +/-5% for values below 4000 ppmv. ULOD_FLAG: -7777 ULOD_VALUE: N/A LLOD_FLAG: -8888 LLOD_VALUE: N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO: David Noone: Oregon State University, nooned@oregonstate.edu; or Dean Henze at henzede@oregonstate.edu. PROJECT_INFO: ORACLES Mission August-September 2017; Sao Tome and Ascension Island. STIPULATIONS_ON_USE: Until made public, only the ORACLES science team is allowed to use this data, per the ORACLES data protocol. OTHER_COMMENTS: Transit flights: All transit flights were almost entirely done at constant a altitude 6-7km above sea level, and are likely not useful for most analyses. No reference data is available to time synchronize WISPER data during transit flights. Further, any outlying data have not been removed for these flights. However, a basic calibration of humidity and isotope ratios has been performed. Transit flight data is not recommended for scientific research unless the PI or Dean Henze are contacted first. Research flights: The following is a list of flights with missing data or outlying data qualtiy. If data from these days stand out in your analysis, caution should be taken: 09/06/2016 and 09/08/2016: No data available. 09/24/2016: Pic2 instrument had multiple periods of poor performance during the flight. These segments of bad data have been removed. 08/12/2017 and 08/13/2017: Pic1 was not operating normally, and the calibration for these days was different from the remaining days. An alternate calibration method was used. Pic1 isotope data for humidities below 1000 ppmv should not be used. 10/02/2018: No data available. 10/10/2018: CVI data for this flight, including the flow and enhancement data, should not be used. The following is a list of flights where the time lag between Pic1 and Pic2 was non-standard: 09/10/2016: Some segments of data can have up to a 20s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. 09/24/2016: Some segments of data can have up to a 10s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. 09/27/2018: Some segments of data can have up to a 15s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. All flights between and including 10/12/2018 - 10/23/2018: Flow controller for Pic2 line was off. Some segments of data can have up to a 15s offset, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. REVISION: R2 R2: Calibrated and time synchronized dataset with quality control, suitable for scientific research. A few outliers in the cloud data still exist but are easily identifiable.     45,1001 Howes, C and Saide, P University of California Los Angeles Estimated smoke age from the forecasting model WRF-AAM ORACLES 1,1 2018, 10, 03, 2021, 02, 22 1 Start_UTC, seconds, seconds from 0000 UTC on the data start day 3 1,1,1 -9999.99, -9999.99, -9999.99 Model_Age, days, WRF-AAM calculated smoke plume age Model_RH, percent [%], WRF-AAM relative humidity Model_ext532, Mm{-1}, WRF-AAM aerosol scattering at 532nm 0 28 PI_CONTACT_INFO: Calvin Howes, calvinhowes@ucla.edu Platform: Wallops P-3 N426NA LOCATION: See separate housekeeping data at https://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles/P3/Hskping ASSOCIATED_DATA: See Oracles archive on ESPO data archive at https://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles/ INSTRUMENT_INFO: N/A DATA_INFO: Model-derived estimates for aerosol time since emission (age) of up to two weeks were calculated using the Weather Research and Aerosol Aware Microphysics (WRF-AAM) Model (Thompson and Eidhammer, 2014) run in forecasting mode. The model releases tracers tagged to CO at the location of biomass burning emissions for each day and keeps track of them for two weeks in fourteen tracers. Smoke age is estimated as the mean of the tracer concentration distribution. The model configuration is similar to that in Saide et al, (2016), with the 12-km spatial resolution regional model encompassing a domain (410S-140N, 340W-510E) sufficiently large to capture almost all contributing fires from the African continent. The forecasts are initialized daily and driven by the National Center for Environmental Prediction Global Forecasting System. Daily smoke emissions from the Quick Fire Emissions Dataset (Darmenov and da Silva, 2013) are scaled to match satellite-derived aerosol optical depth based on a near-real time inversion algorithm described in Saide et al, (2016). Smoke emissions are released into the model surface layer using a prescribed diurnal cycle. Aerosols and tracers are advected thereafter according to the model physics UNCERTAINTY: N/A ULOD_FLAG: -7777 ULOD_VALUE: N/A LLOD_FLAG: -8888 LLOD_VALUE: N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO: Calvin Howes, calvinhowes@ucla.edu PROJECT_INFO: See project overview at https://espo.nasa.gov/ORACLES/content/ORACLES STIPULATIONS_ON_USE: Please contact PI or DM with questions on best use practices and instrumentation caveats that are not explicitly published here. Otherwise, ORACLES data management protocols apply. REVISION: R0 OTHER_COMMENTS: None R0: final data Start_UTC, Model_Age, Model_RH, Model_ext532

Subsetting variables#

You can take a data array which is a single variable using a single square bracket, whereas if you want it as a dataset (with coordinates and such, and multiple variables), you would use two brackets

air_temp = ds['Static_Air_Temp']

sghowell@hawaii.edu; phone: 808-956-5185; address: Univ. Hawaii Dep't Ocean, 1000 Pope Rd, Honolulu, HI 96822 PLATFORM: NASA P-3B, using a solid diffuser inlet on the port side outside the front cabin. LOCATION: Contained in aircraft data files. ASSOCIATED_DATA: N/A INSTRUMENT_INFO: DATA_INFO: Two TSI 3563 nephelometers were plumbed in series in the front of the plane with a 1 micrometer 50% size cut impactor optionally in line between them, electronically controlled via a 3-way valve. Flow was controlled at 30 liters/minute (volumetric). The TSI Neph scattering coefficients have been corrected for 0 - 180 degrees from the nephelometer detection angles (7 - 170 degrees) based on Anderson and Ogren, Aerosol Science and Technology, 1998. Two Radiance Research M903 nephelometers were operated in parallel at 5 lpm in the rear of the plane. RRDry was operated at ambient relative humidity while RRWet relative humidity was maintained near 80-85 % via a humidity controller upstream. The RR nephelometers' stock filters were replaced with Corion CA-550 80 nm bandpass filters for an effective operating wavelength of 540+/-3 nm (the RR flash lamps have a blue bias). Calibrations were performed in field with refrigerant R-134A (1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane). Measurements are reported at 1 Hz, but mixing time in the nephelometers is about 6 seconds. While negative values are physically absurd, they are a product of noise in the system and are left in so averages are valid. Scattering measurements have been adjusted to standard conditions (1013.25 hPa, 273.15 K), but not for the RH changes that would ensue. UNCERTAINTY: Accuracy for the TSI Nephs is roughly 10%, and depends on averaging times. The RR Nephs lack geometric corrections, so are less accurate, by up to 50% in coarse aerosol (though that was rare in ORACLES). Temperature errors are about 0.5 C and RH errors are roughly 3%. Pressure errors are about 1.5%. Rear PSAP lambda-average Single scattering albedo for 660 nm light 0 74 PI_CONTACT_INFO: sghowell@hawaii.edu; phone: 808-956-5185; University of Hawaii Department of Oceanography, 1000 Pope Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822 PLATFORM: NASA P-3B, using a solid diffuser (SDI; 2016-18) and counterflow virtual impactor (CVI; 2017-18) inlet on the port side outside the front cabin. LOCATION: Contained in aircraft data files. ASSOCIATED_DATA: N/A INSTRUMENT_INFO: DATA_INFO: Two Radiance Research 3-wavelength PSAPS were operated during ORACLES 2016 - 2018 both measuring total aerosol absorption (for aerosol inlet efficiencies see McNaughton (Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 2007)). To reduce artifacts due to changing RH, the PSAP optical block was heated to approximately 50 C during 2016 and 30 C during 2017/18. Absorption data provided here are calculated by the PSAP firmware, which has known calculation issues, decreasing signal to noise. Campaigns 2016/17 used the original PSAP firmware, while both PSAPs were upgraded to version 2.03 for 2018 to improve raw data reporting. The new firmware version for 2018 reduces smoothing times, increasing second by second noise (see UNCERTAINTY info below). The PSAP firmware absorption includes a Bond (2007) correction which was undone before Virkkula (2010) corrections were applied to all PSAP measurements. This submission data set provides both wavelength- specific ("Lambda_Spec_") and wavelength-averaged ("Lambda_Avg_") Virkkula corrections (for details see Table 1 in Virkkula (Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 2010)). The Virkkula (2010) scattering correction and SSA use (interpolated Scat470/Scat530/Scat660) data from the TSI nephelometer (corrected according to Anderson and Ogren; Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 1998). For the 2016 and 2018 campaigns TSI nephelometer total scattering is used exclusively. For the year 2017 both total ("TSI_Impactor_Status" is 1) and submicron ("TSI_Impactor_Status" is 0) TSI nephelometer measurements are used because only one TSI nephelometer was operational (this TSI Neph was operated behind an impactor occasionally during 2017). The effect of submicron TSI measurements on the Virkkula (2010) scattering correction is expected to be small in the free troposphere in the absence of dust but does affect data in the marine boundary layer (MBL) due to sea spray. MBL data during times where submicron TSI measurements were used should be interpreted with care. An alternative to submicrometer TSI data exists via Radiance Research M903 nephelometer data (at 540 nm light). The M903 nephelometer data can be found in the SCAT_P3_YYYYMMDD_RX.ict files. During ORACLES 2016 both PSAPS were operated on the SDI exclusively and in parallel on the second rack from the inlet. After an instrument rearrangement aboard the NASA P-3B, ORACLES campaigns 2017 and 2018 had one PSAP on the front rack next to the SDI/CVI (Front PSAP operated on CVI occasionally), while the other PSAP was on the 4th rack (Rear PSAP operated on the SDI at all times). Variable names designate PSAP unit as either "_Rear" or "_Front" for all 3 years for uniformity of data sets even though instruments were operated on the same rack during 2016. UNCERTAINTY:1 Hz data have considerable random noise. Averaging for 240 - 300 s gives ~ 0.5 Mm^^{-1} errors after Virkkula (2010) corrections (Anderson (JGR; 2009), McNaughton (ACP; 2009), McNaughton (ACP; 2011)). Rapid RH changes also cause periods of increased error. To reduce noise and to achieve closure between both instruments a minimum average of 10 seconds is recommended for both PSAPs. ChamberTemp is degree celcius; ChamberPres is in mBar. PI_CONTACT_INFO:smalljen@hawaii.edu PLATFORM:NASA P-3 Orion aircraft LOCATION:Latitude Longitude and Altitude included in data records from P-3 Cabin Data ASSOCIATED_DATA:N/A INSTRUMENT_INFO:Flight-Probe Dual-Range Phase Doppler Interferometer Data From Aritum Model 3321. There are no flags. If there is no data present at a certain time there were no clouds. Comparisons with other cloud probe/instruments does not require any conversion. Measurement Technique described in Chuang P. Y. and Saw and E. W. Small J. D. and Shaw R. A. and Sipperley C. M. and Payne and G. A. and Bachalo W. D. 2008: Airborne phase Doppler interferometry for cloud microphysical measurements Aerosol Sci. Tech. 42 685-703. DATA_INFO:Cloud droplet measurements are reported at observed altitude (temperature and pressure). Cloud drops are measured indivdually and then binned into the the size reanges described above. Units are in micrometers UNCERTAINTY:drop sizing is +/- 0.5 um ULOD_FLAG:-7777 ULOD_VALUE:N/A LLOD_FLAG:-8888 LLOD_VALUE:N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO:Jennifer Griswold (smalljen@hawaii.edu) PROJECT_INFO:ORACLES 2018 STIPULATIONS_ON_USE:These are level R2 and can be used for publication. It is advised that users consult with the PI for information and questions regarding the data product. OTHER_COMMENTS:Data are logarithmically binned. REVISION:R2 R2:View volumes were calculated with new automated algorithm. Data collection was filtered to reduce aircraft noise during flight. R1:Data is time synched with UND CAS and CDP and uses preliminary concentration values. Later revisions will use a comprehenisve method to derive view volume length and thus the concentration. LOCATION: Aircraft location data decribed elsewhere. ASSOCIATED_DATA: see http://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles INSTRUMENT_INFO: The WISPER system centers around two Water Vapor Isotopic Analyzers (Picarro L2120-i and L2120-fi) which utilize cavity-ringdown tunable diode laser spectoscopy. Air for in-situ sampling was collected through two inlets: one was the isokinetic SDI inlet and the other was the Oregon State University counterflow virtual impactor (CVI) inlet. The first analyzer, Pic1, was capable of sampling from either the SDI or CVI inlet, while the second analyzer, Pic2, sampled from only the SDI inlet. For the 2016 deployment, the CVI was not present and therefore only Pic2 variables are available. DATA_INFO: Variables with subscript 'tot2' (i.e. h2o_tot2, dD_tot2, ...) are Pic2 measurements via the SDI inlet, which are total water measurements (vapor+liquid+ice). Since only Pic2 was present for the 2016 deployment, only subscript 2 variables are present. Variables with subscript 'tot1' are Pic1 measurements via the SDI inlet, and are total water measurements as well. Variables with subcript cld (i.e. h2o_cld, dD_cld, ...) are Pic1 measurements of cloud water only (liquid+ice), via the CVI. 'tot1' and 'cld' variables are present for both the 2017 and 2018 deployments. Cloud data where the measured humidity after enchancement is less than 800 ppmv has been masked. However, even at 800 ppmv the isotope ratio measurements are not highly precise or acaurate. If better quality is desired, it is recommended to mask data for humidities below 1500 ppmv. See the 'OTHER_COMMENTS' section below for an overview of instrument performance and data quality for particular flights. Due to incomplete isotope ratio calibration data, the isotope variables in this dataset should not be compared to other datasets on an absolute scale or used for analyses where an absolute scale is necessary. See the section 'UNCERTAINTY' for more info. UNCERTAINTY: Precision: Precision: Estimates of isotope ratio precisions are included as standard deviation columns. The precision for humidity is likely negligible for most studies and columns are not included - if needed, they can assumed to be 35 ppmv for humidities below 6000 ppmv, and 15 ppmv for higher humidities; Accuracy: Due to incomplete absolute calibration data, the isotope variables in this dataset should not be compared to other datasets on an absolute scale or used for analyses where an absolute scale is necessary. However, the dataset is self consistent - i.e. relative changes in values within a flight, between separate flights, and between separate years can be taken as real, within uncertainty. For an estimate of these uncertainties, please contact the PI (see DM_CONTACT_INFO below), or Dean Henze at henzede@oregonstate.edu. Absolute calibration of the humidity measurements can be assumed, with an accuracy of +/-2.5% for values above 6000 ppmv, +/-3.5% for values between 4000 and 6000 ppmv, and +/-5% for values below 4000 ppmv. ULOD_FLAG: -7777 ULOD_VALUE: N/A LLOD_FLAG: -8888 LLOD_VALUE: N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO: David Noone: Oregon State University, nooned@oregonstate.edu; or Dean Henze at henzede@oregonstate.edu. PROJECT_INFO: ORACLES Mission August-September 2017; Sao Tome and Ascension Island. STIPULATIONS_ON_USE: Until made public, only the ORACLES science team is allowed to use this data, per the ORACLES data protocol. OTHER_COMMENTS: Transit flights: All transit flights were almost entirely done at constant a altitude 6-7km above sea level, and are likely not useful for most analyses. No reference data is available to time synchronize WISPER data during transit flights. Further, any outlying data have not been removed for these flights. However, a basic calibration of humidity and isotope ratios has been performed. Transit flight data is not recommended for scientific research unless the PI or Dean Henze are contacted first. Research flights: The following is a list of flights with missing data or outlying data qualtiy. If data from these days stand out in your analysis, caution should be taken: 09/06/2016 and 09/08/2016: No data available. 09/24/2016: Pic2 instrument had multiple periods of poor performance during the flight. These segments of bad data have been removed. 08/12/2017 and 08/13/2017: Pic1 was not operating normally, and the calibration for these days was different from the remaining days. An alternate calibration method was used. Pic1 isotope data for humidities below 1000 ppmv should not be used. 10/02/2018: No data available. 10/10/2018: CVI data for this flight, including the flow and enhancement data, should not be used. The following is a list of flights where the time lag between Pic1 and Pic2 was non-standard: 09/10/2016: Some segments of data can have up to a 20s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. 09/24/2016: Some segments of data can have up to a 10s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. 09/27/2018: Some segments of data can have up to a 15s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. All flights between and including 10/12/2018 - 10/23/2018: Flow controller for Pic2 line was off. Some segments of data can have up to a 15s offset, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. REVISION: R2 R2: Calibrated and time synchronized dataset with quality control, suitable for scientific research. A few outliers in the cloud data still exist but are easily identifiable.     header_Model-age_P3_20181003_R0_ict :
    45,1001 Howes, C and Saide, P University of California Los Angeles Estimated smoke age from the forecasting model WRF-AAM ORACLES 1,1 2018, 10, 03, 2021, 02, 22 1 Start_UTC, seconds, seconds from 0000 UTC on the data start day 3 1,1,1 -9999.99, -9999.99, -9999.99 Model_Age, days, WRF-AAM calculated smoke plume age Model_RH, percent [%], WRF-AAM relative humidity Model_ext532, Mm{-1}, WRF-AAM aerosol scattering at 532nm 0 28 PI_CONTACT_INFO: Calvin Howes, calvinhowes@ucla.edu Platform: Wallops P-3 N426NA LOCATION: See separate housekeeping data at https://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles/P3/Hskping ASSOCIATED_DATA: See Oracles archive on ESPO data archive at https://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles/ INSTRUMENT_INFO: N/A DATA_INFO: Model-derived estimates for aerosol time since emission (age) of up to two weeks were calculated using the Weather Research and Aerosol Aware Microphysics (WRF-AAM) Model (Thompson and Eidhammer, 2014) run in forecasting mode. The model releases tracers tagged to CO at the location of biomass burning emissions for each day and keeps track of them for two weeks in fourteen tracers. Smoke age is estimated as the mean of the tracer concentration distribution. The model configuration is similar to that in Saide et al, (2016), with the 12-km spatial resolution regional model encompassing a domain (410S-140N, 340W-510E) sufficiently large to capture almost all contributing fires from the African continent. The forecasts are initialized daily and driven by the National Center for Environmental Prediction Global Forecasting System. Daily smoke emissions from the Quick Fire Emissions Dataset (Darmenov and da Silva, 2013) are scaled to match satellite-derived aerosol optical depth based on a near-real time inversion algorithm described in Saide et al, (2016). Smoke emissions are released into the model surface layer using a prescribed diurnal cycle. Aerosols and tracers are advected thereafter according to the model physics UNCERTAINTY: N/A ULOD_FLAG: -7777 ULOD_VALUE: N/A LLOD_FLAG: -8888 LLOD_VALUE: N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO: Calvin Howes, calvinhowes@ucla.edu PROJECT_INFO: See project overview at https://espo.nasa.gov/ORACLES/content/ORACLES STIPULATIONS_ON_USE: Please contact PI or DM with questions on best use practices and instrumentation caveats that are not explicitly published here. Otherwise, ORACLES data management protocols apply. REVISION: R0 OTHER_COMMENTS: None R0: final data Start_UTC, Model_Age, Model_RH, Model_ext532

sghowell@hawaii.edu; phone: 808-956-5185; address: Univ. Hawaii Dep't Ocean, 1000 Pope Rd, Honolulu, HI 96822 PLATFORM: NASA P-3B, using a solid diffuser inlet on the port side outside the front cabin. LOCATION: Contained in aircraft data files. ASSOCIATED_DATA: N/A INSTRUMENT_INFO: DATA_INFO: Two TSI 3563 nephelometers were plumbed in series in the front of the plane with a 1 micrometer 50% size cut impactor optionally in line between them, electronically controlled via a 3-way valve. Flow was controlled at 30 liters/minute (volumetric). The TSI Neph scattering coefficients have been corrected for 0 - 180 degrees from the nephelometer detection angles (7 - 170 degrees) based on Anderson and Ogren, Aerosol Science and Technology, 1998. Two Radiance Research M903 nephelometers were operated in parallel at 5 lpm in the rear of the plane. RRDry was operated at ambient relative humidity while RRWet relative humidity was maintained near 80-85 % via a humidity controller upstream. The RR nephelometers' stock filters were replaced with Corion CA-550 80 nm bandpass filters for an effective operating wavelength of 540+/-3 nm (the RR flash lamps have a blue bias). Calibrations were performed in field with refrigerant R-134A (1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane). Measurements are reported at 1 Hz, but mixing time in the nephelometers is about 6 seconds. While negative values are physically absurd, they are a product of noise in the system and are left in so averages are valid. Scattering measurements have been adjusted to standard conditions (1013.25 hPa, 273.15 K), but not for the RH changes that would ensue. UNCERTAINTY: Accuracy for the TSI Nephs is roughly 10%, and depends on averaging times. The RR Nephs lack geometric corrections, so are less accurate, by up to 50% in coarse aerosol (though that was rare in ORACLES). Temperature errors are about 0.5 C and RH errors are roughly 3%. Pressure errors are about 1.5%. ULOD_FLAG: -7777 ULOD_VALUE: N/A LLOD_FLAG: -8888 LLOD_VALUE: N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO: freitag@hawaii.edu; phone: 808-956-7777; University of Hawaii Department of Oceanography, 1000 Pope Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822 PROJECT_INFO: ORACLES 2018 deployment to Sao Tome, September and October, https://espo.nasa.gov/missions/oracles STIPULATIONS_ON_USE: This is the revised dataset with all corrections implemented. However, it is strongly recommended to consult the PI for any updates and interpretation of measurements before publication. OTHER_COMMENTS: N/A REVISION: R1 R1: The following changes have been made: The manual cloud shatter mask was amended using King hot wire probe LWC and Cloud Droplet Probe droplet concentration measurements were necessary. Nephelometer data have been time shifted and are aligned with wing probe PCASP instrument now. TSI I backscattering data for all wavelengths are masked for all flights now since the sensor did not work properly. TSI I 450 nm scattering also tended to drift upward during flight and was recalibrated by repeatedly zeroing the TSI I instrument during flight. TSI II was not operational until October 7th, 2018. R0: This is a preliminary dataset; not all corrections have been implemented. In particular, cloud droplet shatter may still be a problem; a manual mask was applied, but not fully examined. Periods when filters were applied in flight to check for leaks have been removed. A rough correction has been made to account for delays in sample lines synchronizing the TSI 3563 and M903 nephelometers with wing probe PCASP instrument. Post-deployment calibrations are not complete. While RH probes in TSI 3563 and M903 have been corrected based on lab calibrations, RH inside TSI nephelometer is a long-standing problem since the sample is heated by the light and an RH probe cannot be placed in the actual sampling region. Rear PSAP lambda-average Single scattering albedo for 660 nm light 0 74 PI_CONTACT_INFO: sghowell@hawaii.edu; phone: 808-956-5185; University of Hawaii Department of Oceanography, 1000 Pope Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822 PLATFORM: NASA P-3B, using a solid diffuser (SDI; 2016-18) and counterflow virtual impactor (CVI; 2017-18) inlet on the port side outside the front cabin. LOCATION: Contained in aircraft data files. ASSOCIATED_DATA: N/A INSTRUMENT_INFO: DATA_INFO: Two Radiance Research 3-wavelength PSAPS were operated during ORACLES 2016 - 2018 both measuring total aerosol absorption (for aerosol inlet efficiencies see McNaughton (Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 2007)). To reduce artifacts due to changing RH, the PSAP optical block was heated to approximately 50 C during 2016 and 30 C during 2017/18. Absorption data provided here are calculated by the PSAP firmware, which has known calculation issues, decreasing signal to noise. Campaigns 2016/17 used the original PSAP firmware, while both PSAPs were upgraded to version 2.03 for 2018 to improve raw data reporting. The new firmware version for 2018 reduces smoothing times, increasing second by second noise (see UNCERTAINTY info below). The PSAP firmware absorption includes a Bond (2007) correction which was undone before Virkkula (2010) corrections were applied to all PSAP measurements. This submission data set provides both wavelength- specific ("Lambda_Spec_") and wavelength-averaged ("Lambda_Avg_") Virkkula corrections (for details see Table 1 in Virkkula (Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 2010)). The Virkkula (2010) scattering correction and SSA use (interpolated Scat470/Scat530/Scat660) data from the TSI nephelometer (corrected according to Anderson and Ogren; Aerosol Sci. Technol.; 1998). For the 2016 and 2018 campaigns TSI nephelometer total scattering is used exclusively. For the year 2017 both total ("TSI_Impactor_Status" is 1) and submicron ("TSI_Impactor_Status" is 0) TSI nephelometer measurements are used because only one TSI nephelometer was operational (this TSI Neph was operated behind an impactor occasionally during 2017). The effect of submicron TSI measurements on the Virkkula (2010) scattering correction is expected to be small in the free troposphere in the absence of dust but does affect data in the marine boundary layer (MBL) due to sea spray. MBL data during times where submicron TSI measurements were used should be interpreted with care. An alternative to submicrometer TSI data exists via Radiance Research M903 nephelometer data (at 540 nm light). The M903 nephelometer data can be found in the SCAT_P3_YYYYMMDD_RX.ict files. During ORACLES 2016 both PSAPS were operated on the SDI exclusively and in parallel on the second rack from the inlet. After an instrument rearrangement aboard the NASA P-3B, ORACLES campaigns 2017 and 2018 had one PSAP on the front rack next to the SDI/CVI (Front PSAP operated on CVI occasionally), while the other PSAP was on the 4th rack (Rear PSAP operated on the SDI at all times). Variable names designate PSAP unit as either "_Rear" or "_Front" for all 3 years for uniformity of data sets even though instruments were operated on the same rack during 2016. UNCERTAINTY:1 Hz data have considerable random noise. Averaging for 240 - 300 s gives ~ 0.5 Mm^^{-1} errors after Virkkula (2010) corrections (Anderson (JGR; 2009), McNaughton (ACP; 2009), McNaughton (ACP; 2011)). Rapid RH changes also cause periods of increased error. To reduce noise and to achieve closure between both instruments a minimum average of 10 seconds is recommended for both PSAPs. Previous 2017/18 submissions also had variables names for "Lambda_Spec_XXXX_Rear" interchanged with "Lambda_Avg_XXXX_Front". Besides cloud shatter and manual filter periods experimental data sets are also masked in this release: Denuded PSAP data (Front PSAP; 2017 campaign) have been masked in this release since charring affected these absorption measurements. PSAP measurements behind the CVI (Front PSAP; 2017/18 campaign) are also masked and will be submitted in separate files. The PSAP spot size correction has been updated for all 3 years roughly increasing all PSAP ("_Rear" and "_Front") measurements by 5%. R1: The following changes have been made: The manual cloud shatter mask was amended using King hot wire probe LWC and Cloud Droplet Probe droplet concentration measurements were necessary. Absorption data have been time shifted and are aligned with wing probe PCASP instrument now. Flow calibrations for Front and Rear PSAP have been applied. R0: This is a preliminary dataset and not all corrections have been implemented. In particular, cloud droplet shatter may still be a problem (manual mask was applied, but not fully examined). CVI data are masked for this release. Periods when filters were applied in flight to check for leaks have been removed. Flow calibrations for both PSAPs have been applied. A rough correction has been made to account for delays in sample lines synchronizing the PSAPs with wing probe PCASP instrument. Post-deployment calibrations are not complete. INSTRUMENT_INFO:Flight-Probe Dual-Range Phase Doppler Interferometer Data From Aritum Model 3321. There are no flags. If there is no data present at a certain time there were no clouds. Comparisons with other cloud probe/instruments does not require any conversion. Measurement Technique described in Chuang P. Y. and Saw and E. W. Small J. D. and Shaw R. A. and Sipperley C. M. and Payne and G. A. and Bachalo W. D. 2008: Airborne phase Doppler interferometry for cloud microphysical measurements Aerosol Sci. Tech. 42 685-703. DATA_INFO:Cloud droplet measurements are reported at observed altitude (temperature and pressure). Cloud drops are measured indivdually and then binned into the the size reanges described above. Units are in micrometers UNCERTAINTY:drop sizing is +/- 0.5 um ULOD_FLAG:-7777 ULOD_VALUE:N/A LLOD_FLAG:-8888 LLOD_VALUE:N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO:Jennifer Griswold (smalljen@hawaii.edu) PROJECT_INFO:ORACLES 2018 STIPULATIONS_ON_USE:These are level R2 and can be used for publication. It is advised that users consult with the PI for information and questions regarding the data product. OTHER_COMMENTS:Data are logarithmically binned. REVISION:R2 R2:View volumes were calculated with new automated algorithm. Data collection was filtered to reduce aircraft noise during flight. R1:Data is time synched with UND CAS and CDP and uses preliminary concentration values. Later revisions will use a comprehenisve method to derive view volume length and thus the concentration. LOCATION: Aircraft location data decribed elsewhere. ASSOCIATED_DATA: see http://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles INSTRUMENT_INFO: The WISPER system centers around two Water Vapor Isotopic Analyzers (Picarro L2120-i and L2120-fi) which utilize cavity-ringdown tunable diode laser spectoscopy. Air for in-situ sampling was collected through two inlets: one was the isokinetic SDI inlet and the other was the Oregon State University counterflow virtual impactor (CVI) inlet. The first analyzer, Pic1, was capable of sampling from either the SDI or CVI inlet, while the second analyzer, Pic2, sampled from only the SDI inlet. For the 2016 deployment, the CVI was not present and therefore only Pic2 variables are available. DATA_INFO: Variables with subscript 'tot2' (i.e. h2o_tot2, dD_tot2, ...) are Pic2 measurements via the SDI inlet, which are total water measurements (vapor+liquid+ice). Since only Pic2 was present for the 2016 deployment, only subscript 2 variables are present. Variables with subscript 'tot1' are Pic1 measurements via the SDI inlet, and are total water measurements as well. Variables with subcript cld (i.e. h2o_cld, dD_cld, ...) are Pic1 measurements of cloud water only (liquid+ice), via the CVI. 'tot1' and 'cld' variables are present for both the 2017 and 2018 deployments. Cloud data where the measured humidity after enchancement is less than 800 ppmv has been masked. However, even at 800 ppmv the isotope ratio measurements are not highly precise or acaurate. If better quality is desired, it is recommended to mask data for humidities below 1500 ppmv. See the 'OTHER_COMMENTS' section below for an overview of instrument performance and data quality for particular flights. Due to incomplete isotope ratio calibration data, the isotope variables in this dataset should not be compared to other datasets on an absolute scale or used for analyses where an absolute scale is necessary. See the section 'UNCERTAINTY' for more info. UNCERTAINTY: Precision: Precision: Estimates of isotope ratio precisions are included as standard deviation columns. The precision for humidity is likely negligible for most studies and columns are not included - if needed, they can assumed to be 35 ppmv for humidities below 6000 ppmv, and 15 ppmv for higher humidities; Accuracy: Due to incomplete absolute calibration data, the isotope variables in this dataset should not be compared to other datasets on an absolute scale or used for analyses where an absolute scale is necessary. However, the dataset is self consistent - i.e. relative changes in values within a flight, between separate flights, and between separate years can be taken as real, within uncertainty. For an estimate of these uncertainties, please contact the PI (see DM_CONTACT_INFO below), or Dean Henze at henzede@oregonstate.edu. Absolute calibration of the humidity measurements can be assumed, with an accuracy of +/-2.5% for values above 6000 ppmv, +/-3.5% for values between 4000 and 6000 ppmv, and +/-5% for values below 4000 ppmv. ULOD_FLAG: -7777 ULOD_VALUE: N/A LLOD_FLAG: -8888 LLOD_VALUE: N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO: David Noone: Oregon State University, nooned@oregonstate.edu; or Dean Henze at henzede@oregonstate.edu. PROJECT_INFO: ORACLES Mission August-September 2017; Sao Tome and Ascension Island. STIPULATIONS_ON_USE: Until made public, only the ORACLES science team is allowed to use this data, per the ORACLES data protocol. OTHER_COMMENTS: Transit flights: All transit flights were almost entirely done at constant a altitude 6-7km above sea level, and are likely not useful for most analyses. No reference data is available to time synchronize WISPER data during transit flights. Further, any outlying data have not been removed for these flights. However, a basic calibration of humidity and isotope ratios has been performed. Transit flight data is not recommended for scientific research unless the PI or Dean Henze are contacted first. Research flights: The following is a list of flights with missing data or outlying data qualtiy. If data from these days stand out in your analysis, caution should be taken: 09/06/2016 and 09/08/2016: No data available. 09/24/2016: Pic2 instrument had multiple periods of poor performance during the flight. These segments of bad data have been removed. 08/12/2017 and 08/13/2017: Pic1 was not operating normally, and the calibration for these days was different from the remaining days. An alternate calibration method was used. Pic1 isotope data for humidities below 1000 ppmv should not be used. 10/02/2018: No data available. 10/10/2018: CVI data for this flight, including the flow and enhancement data, should not be used. The following is a list of flights where the time lag between Pic1 and Pic2 was non-standard: 09/10/2016: Some segments of data can have up to a 20s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. 09/24/2016: Some segments of data can have up to a 10s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. 09/27/2018: Some segments of data can have up to a 15s lag, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. All flights between and including 10/12/2018 - 10/23/2018: Flow controller for Pic2 line was off. Some segments of data can have up to a 15s offset, although most data is better. If higher accuracy is needed, time synchronization should be performed on individual segments. REVISION: R2 R2: Calibrated and time synchronized dataset with quality control, suitable for scientific research. A few outliers in the cloud data still exist but are easily identifiable. R1: Preliminary calibration.     45,1001 Howes, C and Saide, P University of California Los Angeles Estimated smoke age from the forecasting model WRF-AAM ORACLES 1,1 2018, 10, 03, 2021, 02, 22 1 Start_UTC, seconds, seconds from 0000 UTC on the data start day 3 1,1,1 -9999.99, -9999.99, -9999.99 Model_Age, days, WRF-AAM calculated smoke plume age Model_RH, percent [%], WRF-AAM relative humidity Model_ext532, Mm{-1}, WRF-AAM aerosol scattering at 532nm 0 28 PI_CONTACT_INFO: Calvin Howes, calvinhowes@ucla.edu Platform: Wallops P-3 N426NA LOCATION: See separate housekeeping data at https://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles/P3/Hskping ASSOCIATED_DATA: See Oracles archive on ESPO data archive at https://espoarchive.nasa.gov/archive/browse/oracles/ INSTRUMENT_INFO: N/A DATA_INFO: Model-derived estimates for aerosol time since emission (age) of up to two weeks were calculated using the Weather Research and Aerosol Aware Microphysics (WRF-AAM) Model (Thompson and Eidhammer, 2014) run in forecasting mode. The model releases tracers tagged to CO at the location of biomass burning emissions for each day and keeps track of them for two weeks in fourteen tracers. Smoke age is estimated as the mean of the tracer concentration distribution. The model configuration is similar to that in Saide et al, (2016), with the 12-km spatial resolution regional model encompassing a domain (410S-140N, 340W-510E) sufficiently large to capture almost all contributing fires from the African continent. The forecasts are initialized daily and driven by the National Center for Environmental Prediction Global Forecasting System. Daily smoke emissions from the Quick Fire Emissions Dataset (Darmenov and da Silva, 2013) are scaled to match satellite-derived aerosol optical depth based on a near-real time inversion algorithm described in Saide et al, (2016). Smoke emissions are released into the model surface layer using a prescribed diurnal cycle. Aerosols and tracers are advected thereafter according to the model physics UNCERTAINTY: N/A ULOD_FLAG: -7777 ULOD_VALUE: N/A LLOD_FLAG: -8888 LLOD_VALUE: N/A DM_CONTACT_INFO: Calvin Howes, calvinhowes@ucla.edu PROJECT_INFO: See project overview at https://espo.nasa.gov/ORACLES/content/ORACLES STIPULATIONS_ON_USE: Please contact PI or DM with questions on best use practices and instrumentation caveats that are not explicitly published here. Otherwise, ORACLES data management protocols apply. REVISION: R0 OTHER_COMMENTS: None R0: final data Start_UTC, Model_Age, Model_RH, Model_ext532
